<doc id="292067" wikidata="Q1416088" url="?curid=292067" title="Seminorm">
<text>In mathematics, particularly in functional analysis, a seminorm is like a norm but need not be positive definite. Seminorms are intimately connected with convex sets: every seminorm is the Minkowski functional of some absorbing disk and, conversely, the Minkowski functional of any such set is a seminorm.

A topological vector space is locally convex if and only if its topology is induced by a family of seminorms.

==Definition==

Let formula_1 be a vector space over either the real numbers formula_2 or the complex numbers formula_3 
A real-valued function formula_4 is called a if it satisfies the following two conditions:

# Subadditivity/Triangle inequality: formula_5 for all formula_6
# Absolute homogeneity: formula_7 for all formula_8 and all scalars formula_9

These two conditions imply that formula_10 and that every seminorm formula_11 also has the following property:
Some authors include non-negativity as part of the definition of &quot;seminorm&quot; (and also sometimes of &quot;norm&quot;), although this is not necessary since it follows from the other two properties. 

By definition, a norm on formula_1 is a seminorm that also separates points, meaning that it has the following additional property:
A is a pair formula_13 consisting of a vector space formula_1 and a seminorm formula_11 on formula_16 If the seminorm formula_11 is also a norm then the seminormed space formula_13 is called a .

Since absolute homogeneity implies positive homogeneity, every seminorm is a type of function called a sublinear function. A map formula_4 is called a if it is subadditive and positive homogeneous. Unlike a seminorm, a sublinear function is necessarily nonnegative. Sublinear functions are often encountered in the context of the Hahn–Banach theorem. 
A real-valued function formula_4 is a seminorm if and only if it is a sublinear and balanced function.

==Examples==

==Minkowski functionals and seminorms==
Seminorms on a vector space formula_1 are intimately tied, via Minkowski functionals, to subsets of formula_1 that are convex, balanced, and absorbing. Given such a subset formula_23 of formula_24 the Minkowski functional of formula_23 is a seminorm. Conversely, given a seminorm formula_11 on formula_24 the setsformula_28 and formula_29 are convex, balanced, and absorbing and furthermore, the Minkowski functional of these two sets (as well as of any set lying &quot;in between them&quot;) is formula_30

