==Topologies of seminormed spaces==

===Pseudometrics and the induced topology===

A seminorm formula_11 on formula_1 induces a topology, called the , via the canonical translation-invariant pseudometric formula_113; formula_114 
This topology is Hausdorff if and only if formula_115 is a metric, which occurs if and only if formula_11 is a norm. 
This topology makes formula_1 into a locally convex pseudometrizable topological vector space that has a bounded neighborhood of the origin and a neighborhood basis at the origin consisting of the following open balls (or the closed balls) centered at the origin:
